  "original_title": "\u0dbb\u0da7 \u0d9a\u0da2\u0dd4 \u0d95\u0dc3\u0dd9\u0da7 \u0d9a\u0db1\u0dca\u0db1 \u0dbd\u0dd0\u0db6\u0dd9\u0db1 \u0dc5\u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dab\u0dd4",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Signs that the cashew nut can eat",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Agriculture Minister Mahinda Amaraweera said that Sri Lanka has become self-sufficient in groundnuts and there is no need to import even the variety of cashew required for processing \"jumbo peanuts\".",
        "The Agriculture Minister said that the alternative groundnut variety \"Sri Lanka Jumbo\" cultivated in Sri Lanka is higher in quality than the imported groundnuts.",
        "The Minister of Agriculture stated this while attending the Sri Lanka Jumbo Groundnut Harvesting Program at the Middeniya Thorakolaya Government Seed Farm.",
        "According to the Department of Agriculture, 29 percent of the daily protein requirement for humans can be provided by eating these peanuts.",
        "Due to the increase in meat and fish prices, there is difficulty in getting the required amount of animal protein for the people, but the deficiency can be met due to the protein content of peanuts, says the Department of Agriculture.",
        "The annual requirement of peanuts in Sri Lanka is 30,000 metric tons and the Ministry of Agriculture says that 64,000 metric tons have been harvested from peanut cultivation."
      ],
